revision.text:
The '''Aber Dinlle Fault''' is a SW-NE trending [[Fault (geology)|fault]] in [[North Wales]]. It forms part of the Menai Strait Fault System, with the [[Berw Fault|Berw]] and Dinorwic Faults. It lies close to the [[epicentre]] of the [[1984 Llŷn Peninsula earthquake]], although it is not thought to have been responsible for that event.<ref name="Turbitt">{{cite journal|last=Turbitt|first=T.|author2=Barker E.J. |author3=Browitt C.W.A. |author4=Howells M. |author5=Marrow P.C. |author6=Musson R.M.W. |author7=Newmark R.H. |author8=Redmayne D.W. |author9=Walker A.B. |author10=Jacob A.W.B. |author11=Ryan E. |author12=Ward V.|year=1985|title=The North Wales earthquake of 19 July 1984|journal=Journal of the Geological Society|volume=142|issue=3|doi=10.1144/gsjgs.142.3.0567|url=http://jgs.lyellcollection.org/cgi/content/abstract/142/3/567|accessdate=18 December 2010}}</ref> The fault was active during deposition of [[Ordovician]] rocks in the [[Welsh Basin]]. It was reactivated as a normal fault in the [[Carboniferous]] with a downthrow to the northwest and again reactivated as a reverse fault during [[Late Carboniferous]] [[Inversion (geology)|inversion]] associated with the [[Variscan Orogeny]].<ref name="Tim">{{cite journal|last=Needham|first=T.|author2=Morgan R.|year=1997|title=The East Irish Sea and adjacent basins: new faults or old?|journal=Journal of the Geological Society|volume=154|issue=1|pages=145–150|doi=10.1144/gsjgs.154.1.0145|url=http://jgs.lyellcollection.org/cgi/content/abstract/154/1/145|accessdate=18 December 2010}}</ref>

