:''Not to be confused with British author, [[Alfred Elwes]].'' {{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}} {{Use British English|date=December 2015}} {{Infobox artist | name = Alfred Thomas Elwes | image = Wonders of the bird world (Pl. 11) (7995793158).jpg | imagesize = | caption = [[Huia]] by Alfred Thomas Elwes, from ''Wonders of the bird world'' | birth_name = | birth_date = 1841 | birth_place = [[Livorno|Leghorn]], [[Italy]]<ref>''1911 England Census''</ref> | death_date = 1917 (aged 75)<ref>England & Wales, Civil Registration Death Index, 1916-2007</ref> | death_place = [[Willesden]], [[Middlesex]] | nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] | field = [[Natural history]] [[illustration]] | training = | works = | patrons = | awards = }}
'''Alfred Thomas Elwes''' (bapt. 1 August 1841 – 1917) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] artist and [[natural history]] [[illustrator]] of mammals and birds. For most of his life he lived and worked in England, illustrating various natural history books of the nineteenth century as well as for [[Illustrated London News]].<ref name="Antique 1999">{{cite book|last1=Jackson|first1=Christine E.|title=Dictionary of bird artists of the world.|date=1999|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|location=Woodbridge|isbn=1851492038|page=235}}</ref><ref name="Houfe 1996">{{cite book|last1=Houfe|first1=Simon|title=The dictionary of 19th century British book illustrators and caricaturists|date=1996|publisher=Antique Collector's Club|location=Woodbridge|isbn=1851491937|pages=295|edition=Rev.}}</ref>
==Life and work== Elwes was born in [[Livorno|Leghorn]], Italy, where he was baptised 1 August 1841. His parents were Alfred Elwes and Louisa Anne Elwes.<ref>''Great Britain, Select Births and Baptisms, 1571-1977''</ref> His father was a professor of languages.<ref> ''1851 England Census''</ref> From 1872 to 1877 he was employed by the [[Illustrated London News]] as the chief draftsman of natural history subjects.<ref name="Antique 1999" /> In 1882 Elwes wrote ''How to draw animals, birds and dogs''. He died sometime after 1911<ref>{{cite web|title=Reynard the Fox|url=http://metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/338343|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art|publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> probably around 1917 in Willesden, Middlesex.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Terry|first1=John|title=Elwes Chart 0500|url=http://www.terrys.org.uk/charts/e/elwes500.htm|website=Terrys|publisher=John Terry|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref>
== Family == Elwes was married in Gravesend, Kent on 15 October 1873 to Kate Barnard.<ref name=V&A>{{cite web|title=Drawing|url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O112656/drawing-elwes-alfred-thomas/|website=Victoria and Albert Museum|publisher=Victoria and Albert Museum|accessdate=9 December 2015}}</ref>
== Books illustrated by Elwes == * [https://archive.org/details/neptuneorautobi00burrgoog ''Neptune: Or The Autobiography Of A Newfoundland Dog''] (1869) by E. Burrows * ''The Pleasant History of Reynard the Fox'' (1873) Translated by Thomas Roscoe * [https://archive.org/details/aridethroughhos00gillgoog ''A Ride Through Hostile Africa: With Adventures Among the Boers''] (1881) by Parker Gillmore * [https://archive.org/details/encounterswithw00gillgoog ''Encounters With Wild Beasts''] (1881) by Parker Gillmore * ''How to draw animals, birds and dogs'' (1882) by A. T. Elwes * ''The Amphibion's voyage'' (1885) by Parker Gillmore * ''Uncle Remus'' (1888) by Joel Chandler Harris * [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/29955#/summary ''The birds of our rambles : A companion for the country''] (1891) by [[Charles Dixon (ornithologist)|Charles Dixon]]. * ''A Book of Drawings'' (1891) by A. Bryan, L. Davis, A. T. Elwes et al. * [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/55315#/summary ''The Game Birds And Wild Fowl Of The British Islands: Being A Handbook For The Naturalist And Sportsman''] (1893) by [[Charles Dixon (ornithologist)|Charles Dixon]]. * [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/30759#/summary ''Birds' nests; an introduction to the science of caliology''] (1902) by [[Charles Dixon (ornithologist)|Charles Dixon]]. * ''Chatterbox'' (1904) by et al. W. P. Pycraft * [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/17115#/summary ''Wonders of the bird world''] (1921) by [[Richard Bowdler Sharpe]]. * ''Bird Wonders Of The Zoo'' (Gardner, 1911). Illustrated by A. T. Elwes.
