'''Flower induction''' is the physiological process in the plant by which the [[meristem|shoot apical meristem]] becomes competent to develop [[flower]]s. Biochemical changes at the apex, particularly those caused by [[cytokinins]], accompany this process. Usually flower induction is followed by [[flower differentiation]], with some notable exceptions such as in [[kiwifruit]], where the two processes are separated. Flower induction can be reversed, but flower differentiation is irreversible, because anatomical changes are in place.

